8. Figure 4 has no vertical axis scale at all and so is not easy to
interpret.

Response:
The numerical values of the objective function (the generalized variance) are not interesting, but rather the shape of the function shows that there is a minimum at the true value of each parameter. 

Text changes: 
(caption)
"1D slices of the objective function (generalized variance) for each halo potential parameter. The parameter values are normalized by the true values and show the effect of varying each parameter by $\pm10$\%. The values of the objective function (vertical axis) are not interesting, but note the minima around the truth (1.0) for each parameter."

9. It is difficult to reconcile the remarks in Section 4 on the Orphan
Stream and GD1 with the work of Sanders & Binney referenced in the
Introduction. In Section 4, it is stated that measurement errors are
too large to resolve "the minute differences between debris and
satellite". But, as Sanders & Binney show, even for the "thinnest,
coldest streams", the debris does not trace a single orbit and the
"bias is equally problematic" (Introduction). If the debris does not
trace an orbit for GD1 and the Orphan, then the differences are not
minute, and Rewinder should work.

We like the Sanders & Binney work too, and agree that there is an offset in orbits for even the thinnest streams (e.g. Johnston 1998 for our own statement of the effect). The reason our method is not expected to work for the thinnest/coldest streams is that, while there is always an offset, the offset does depend on the mass of the satellite (see Johnston et al 1998 for the scaling of this offset in energy). Hence, while the _scaled_ offset is always the same, the absolute offset is much smaller for thinner streams. Our method depends critically on being able to measure this offset for each star, so once the measurement errors are big enough, the method will degrade for the thinner streams (see discussion of points 0-2 and figure). This is not a contradiction of the Sanders & Binney work. 

